voice_to_text: What's the dumbest thing you believed as a kid? I used to eat tissues when I was little, not because I was hungry or anything. I just liked how they dissolved on my tongue into this soft papery mush. It started when I was maybe 4. And by the time I was 5, it was basically my secret snack. Mom caught me once in the living room with a Kleenex hanging out of my mouth like I was some kind of tissue eating monster. What are you doing? Spit that out right now. She looked so horrified, I thought I'd done something truly terrible. You cannot eat tissues. You understand me? So I stopped, well, I stopped doing it in front of her. I got sneakier about it. I grab a few tissues from the bathroom and take them to my room. I eat them slowly, one at a time, like they were some kind of forbidden candy. I knew it was wrong because mom had yelled, but I couldn't really understand why it was wrong. They didn't taste bad. They didn't make my stomach hurt. What was the big deal? This went on for months, maybe. I ate a tissue every few days, sometimes more. If I was bored or watching TV in my room, I'd stuff the evidence deep in my trash can so nobody would find the empty tissue boxes. Then one morning I woke up and couldn't breathe through my nose at all. It felt completely Blocked like someone had shoved cotton up there. I was breathing through my mouth, making these weird gasping sounds and my head felt full of pressure. Dad took me to Doctor Morrison that same day. Doctor Morrison looked up my nose with one those light things and made a hmm sound, the kind of sound that means something is definitely wrong. How long has this been going on? Just since this morning, dad said Doctor Morrison pressed around my nose and face, which hurt. There's significant blockage here. I'm referring you to an E N. T. Specialist today. She needs to be seen as soon as possible. The way he said as soon as possible made my stomach drop. That afternoon we were at Doctor Hayes's office. Smelled like antiseptic and had giant pictures of the inside of noses on the walls. Doctor Hayes had kind eyes, but her voice was serious. She stuck this long camera up my nose while I gripped the chair arms trying not to scream. When she pulled it out, she turned to my parents with this. I couldn't read. I need to schedule a procedure. There's excess tissue causing severe obstruction of the nasal passage. My blood went ice cold. Excess tissue. The tissues, the tissues I've been eating, they were up there stuck in my nose. All those months of eating them in secret and they've been traveling up into my nose and building up like a damn. And now they were going To cut me open, to pull them out, and everyone was going to know what I did. Is it serious, mom asked, her voice tight. If we don't remove it soon, she could develop a serious infection. The procedure is straightforward. We'll put her under general anesthesia and extract all the excess tissue. Extract all the tissue? All of it. However many tissues I'd eaten, they were all up there. I wanted to throw up. I wanted to confess everything right there. But what would I even say? Sorry, I've been eating Kleenex for months and now they're stuck in my nose. They'd think I was insane. Mom would be so angry. And the surgery was happening anyway, so what was the point? Don't worry, sweetie, Doctor Hayes said, noticing I'd gone completely white. You'll be asleep. Don't feel anything. That wasn't what I was worried about. The days before the surgery were torture. Every time mom or dad looked at me, they somehow knew that the doctors had figured it out and told them and they were just waiting for me to confess. I couldn't sleep. I kept imagining them pulling soggy wads of Kleenex out of my nose while everyone stood around looking disgusted. The morning of the surgery, I barely spoke in the car. The hospital was massive and cold and smelled like cleaning chemicals. They made me change into a gown with little blue bears on it. A nurse put an IV in my Hand and it hurt, but I was too scared about everything else to care. We're just going to give you some medicine to help you relax, the nurse said, smiling. I didn't want to relax. I wanted to run. In the operating room, someone put a mask over.

voice_to_text: Nannies. What's the worst thing you found out about a family? I've been their nanny for ages. Two kids, sweet as hell. And the parents both worked demanding jobs. So I was there 50 hours a week. I thought we had a great relationship. Everything was perfect for almost two years. Then little things started shifting. The mom started coming home early and just watching me with the kids, standing in doorways with her arms crossed, not saying anything. She started asking weird questions when I gave her my daily update. What did they say about me today? Did they mention me at all? Did they seem excited when I came home? I told her, yes, of course, they always loved seeing her. She'd nod, but her eyes stayed suspicious. One day the older one told me, Mommy asked if I love you more than her. I thought that was strange, but I let it go because kids say all kinds of things and I didn't want to make it into something bigger than it was. the mom started texting me new rules that had never existed before. Don't let the kids sit in your lap anymore. Don't let them call you nicknames. No more baking together because that's something mothers do with their children, not babysitters. No more special songs at bedtime because she wanted to be the one they associated with comfort. The little one cried because she wasn't allowed to hug me goodbye anymore. And I Had to just stand there with my arms at my sides while she sobbed and reached for me. I tried to talk to the mom about it and she smiled tightly and said everything was fine. She just thought we needed clearer professional boundaries. The housekeeper pulled me aside the following week while the mom was upstairs. She looked nervous and kept glancing at the stairs to make sure no one was coming. Be careful, she said quietly. This happened before. I asked her what she meant and she shook her head and walked away without answering. Two days later, I got a text from the mom at 6 in the morning. Don't come in today or ever. You're terminated effective immediately. No explanation, no notice, no Severance, nothing. I tried calling her and she didn't answer. I texted asking what I did wrong and she left me on read. I called the dad and it went straight to voicemail every time. A week later, I got a letter from a lawyer saying that any attempt to contact the children would result in immediate legal action and a restraining order. Spent the next three weeks going over every interaction, trying to figure out what I've done wrong. I couldn't sleep. I barely ate. I'd spent two years with those kids, watch them grow, help then when they cried. And now I wasn't even allowed to say goodbye. Then the dad called me out of nowhere on a Sunday morning. He Was crying before he even said hello. I need to tell you the truth about what happened. He said his wife had a complete breakdown. She'd been building a case against me for almost a year, collecting evidence that I was trying to steal her children. She had a folder on her phone with hundreds of screenshots and photos and videos, drawings the kids made where I was in the picture, text from their iPad where they said they loved me, recording she'd made of the kids saying they missed me when I wasn't there. She showed me the folder and said you were psychologically manipulating our children to love you more than their own mother.

voice_to_text: A simple hug and she immediately sensed that her best friend's kidneys and liver weren't in good condition. As her friend poured out her troubles, Lucy quickly studied all the theoretical knowledge related to brain development on her computer. Once she had absorbed the theories, she used telekinesis to contact Professor Norman, a world renowned brain scientist. Professor could hardly believe that she had managed to read through over 6,000 of his papers in just a few minutes. Lucy offered to recite them to him right there, told him to meet her at 11. The professor was stunned. Lucy projected herself onto the TV screen and explained to the professor that she had absorbed a large amount of synthetic CPH for and her brain utilization rate had reached 28%. This proved the professor's theory when the brain reaches 20% utilization, it will break all barriers like a chain reaction. Lucy said she could no longer feel pain, fear, desire or any other emotions and even her humanity was gradually fading away. She felt lost and sought the professor's guidance. The professor pointed out that the entire purpose of life was to pass on the knowledge one has Learned that there was no higher goal. Therefore, she should, like any simple cell, pass on her knowledge. At that moment, the professor completely enlightened Lucy. She realized she not only had to share her knowledge with humanity, but also had to figure out how to break the shackles of time. She told The professor, she would meet him in 12 hours. Rushing to the airport, she used telekinesis to make a call contacting the local police chief in Paris.

The boy gently tapped his father's bald head, and in the next unreal moment, his own father slaughtered him and simmered him into meat broth. The entire family gathered at the table, slurping the soup as if it were a Celebration, devouring flesh like it was simply dinner. Whenever this family craved meat, they didn't shop, they hunted, dragging whoever they chose into the kitchen and cooking them right there on the spot. Among all the children, the eldest was the most obedient, which is the only reason he survived long enough to make it to college. One day, he even brought home a beautiful girlfriend. The hallway leading to his place was broken and grimy, every inch worn out, and the neighbours stared with a strange, unsettling intensity. That alone was enough to make the girl's nerves tighten. The moment she stepped into Jack's home, she noticed the filthy sink, dishes piled like they've been rotting for months, and a rancid smell heavy in the air. She forced a polite smile, pretending everything was fine. She handed over her gift, but a swarm of kids tore it from her and shredded the cake like starving animals, swallowing even the plastic wrapper. Their mother stormed in, yelling at them, not because they were rude, but because they didn't let her eat first. By now, the girl wanted nothing but escape. Yet Jack's mother blocked her way, insisting she stay for tea. She sat down, looked into the cup, and found Hair and a dead fly floating on top. Her stomach twisted. She couldn't drink a drop. Right then, her boyfriend's father walked in. He stopped staring at the girl. A long, unsettling look that froze the room.

The man stumbled upon a horrifying clue. The beans he dropped were rolling only in one direction, revealing that their offshore watch tower had already begun to tilt. If they didn't evacuate soon, the whole structure would collapse into the sea and bury them without a trace. The worst part was that they had already served two full years. And according to protocol, fresh personnel should have arrived long ago to relieve them. Yet no one ever came. When morale was at its darkest, a lookout spotted a vessel approaching on the horizon, but strangely, there was no radar signature to match it. He assumed it was the long delayed transport ship finally coming to replace them. The captain, however, felt something was profoundly off. Uncertain of who was aboard, he slammed the alarm button and ordered his men into combat readiness, directing their cannons toward the unidentified ship. As the vessel crept closer, every soldier felt their pulse tighten and the entire tower held its breath. Just when the command to fire was about to be given, the captain changed course. He drew his sidearm, passed it to the lookout and ordered him to board a small craft and investigate the ship directly. The lookout hesitated, but duty left no room for refusal. Slowly, his boat edged toward the vessel. He shouted again and again, yet no voice answered. Back up close, the hull was smothered in rust, lifeless, abandoned, a drifting relic that looked every bit like a True phantom ship.

video_description: What lie did you tell your kids to protect them_ Did it work_
voice_to_text: What lie did you tell your kids to protect them? Did it work? I escaped my violent husband four years ago. He went away for what he did to me. My daughter was 2 at the time and my son was just a baby. I moved to a new town, got a job and raised my kids alone. Now my daughter is 6 and my son is 4. They don't remember him at all and they don't know what he did to me. When they asked about their dad, I told them he worked on oil rigs overseas. It was a lie, but it let them be normal kids. Then I checked the mail and my hands started shaking. He was getting out early for good behaviour. His lawyer called and said, my client is seeking full custody. He's a changed man and you have no right to keep his children from him. I had a restraining order and photos from the hospital and court records proving what kind of man he was, but none of that seemed to matter. The hearing was in three months, which meant I had to figure out how to keep my baby safe. The first thing he did was send letters to the kids. His lawyer had gotten our address through the custody paperwork. Birthday cards with money inside and stuffed animals and toys. They had been asking for the return address said, dad. I grabbed every single one before my kids could see And threw them away. Then he started showing up at their and parking across the street every afternoon, watching them walk out. He was never close enough to break the restraining order so the police couldn't touch him. I called the cops three times and every time they said, ma'am, he's not breaking any laws. There's nothing we can do. Then he started waving at the kids through the fence during recess. My daughter came home with this big smile and said, Mommy, there's a nice man who waves at me at school. He told me to tell you hi. My heart sank. He had talked to her and nobody stopped him. I forced a smile and told her, I don't know who that is, baby. Then my own mother betrayed me. She called and said, he reached out to me. He seems so different now. Everyone deserves a second chance. I told her exactly what he did to me and she said, that was a long time ago. People change. I hung up and never called her back. Then he filed the custody papers and his lawyer painted him as a saint. My lawyer called and said, judges love a redemption story. There's a real chance you could lose your kids. I stopped sleeping and barely ate. Then something made everything worse. My daughter came home from school with a teddy bear I had never seen. She said the nice man gave it to her through the fence. He Was grooming my children and there was nothing I could do. Then my mom called and said she was having a birthday dinner and promised he wouldn't be there. My kids begged to see their grandma, so I said yes. Should have trusted my gut. We get there and everything seems fine at first. We're halfway through dinner when the front door opens. He walks in holding flowers and my mom stands up and smiles at him. She set me up. I grab my kids and move toward the back door, but he blocks it. He looks at my daughter and says, hey, sweetheart, I'm your real daddy. Your mommy has been lying to you. My daughter presses against my leg, shaking. I pull out my phone and dial 9, 1 1. He sees the phone and his face changes. He grabs my wrist hard and says, hang up the phone. I don't move. He squeezes tighter and says, I sat in a cell for four years.

video_description: My best friend told me I was too involved with her kids, so I stopped showing up completely.
voice_to_text: My best friend told me I was too involved with her kids, so I stopped showing up completely. I met Crystal in college and we became the kind of friends who would do anything for each other. When her husband walked out while she was six months pregnant with her second child, I moved in for three months and never really left. That was seven years ago. And I became Auntie Laney, the woman who knew her oldest was allergic to strawberries and terrified of thunderstorms, the woman who could get her youngest to sleep when nobody else could. I was the emergency contact at both their schools and the person who held Crystal's hand in the delivery room when her youngest came into the world. I never expected a medal for any of it because I loved those girls like they were my own. And I thought Crystal understood that. About six months ago, Crystal started dating a guy from work and everything shifted. Her new boyfriend had opinions about me from day one, constantly asking why I was always around and suggesting it was strange for a single woman to be so attached to someone else's children. Crystal started canceling our usual weekend plans and having him handle school pickups instead, which he constantly messed up by forgetting backpacks or showing up 20 minutes late. But I told myself this was just an adjustment period and tried to give them space. And came her youngest daughter's seventh birthday. Party. And I overheard a conversation that changed everything. I was in the kitchen grabbing juice boxes when his voice carried in from the living room. It's honestly pathetic, he said, a woman with no family of her own playing pretend with someone else's kids. I froze and waited for Crystal to defend me. Instead, I heard her sigh. I know I've been trying to get her to back off, but she won't take a hint. I walked straight out to the backyard where she was standing. Is that really how you feel about the last seven years? She crossed her arms. He has a point. You're too involved, Laney. Maybe it's time you focused on building your own life instead of borrowing mine. I gave her exactly what she wanted and disappeared from their lives completely. Two weeks later, my phone rang and it was the elementary school telling me that Crystal's youngest was having a severe allergic reaction and they could not reach her mother. I was still listed as emergency contact, so I grabbed my keys and the epi pen I had been carrying in my purse and ran. I made it there in 12 minutes and handed over the epi pen. The nurse administered the shot while I held the oldest daughter in the hallway and let her sob into my shoulder. Twenty minutes later, Crystal finally rushed through the doors with her boyfriend trailing behind her. She spotted me and her face went hard. She Pulled me into an empty classroom and got right in my face. What are you doing here? I told you to back off. I stared at her in disbelief. I just saved your daughter's life. She stepped closer. You had no right to be here. You're not her mother. Laney, stop pretending you have any claim to my children. Something in me snapped. I'm the one who noticed she was developing a peanut allergy three weeks ago. I told you about it and you said I being dramatic. So I bought an EP pen with my own money and I called the school nurse myself to warn her. What exactly did you do, Crystal? Because you couldn't even answer your phone. Her boyfriend stepped forward with his chest puffed out. You need to.
